---
const props = Astro.props;
const { data } = props;
import BeachvilleAccordionItem from "../BeachvilleAccordionItem.astro";
import BeachvilleArtistSection from "../BeachvilleArtistSection.astro";
import BeachvilleListItem from "../BeachvilleListItem.astro";
---

<div id="region-details" class="my-8" >
    
    <!-- Accordion Container -->
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto space-y-8">
      <!-- The Political Weather -->
      <div class="accordion-item bg-white border border-[#FEE96A]/30 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
        <button class="accordion-trigger w-full px-6 py-4 text-left  bg-[#FEE96A]/30 hover:bg-[#FEE96A]/20 transition-colors flex justify-between items-center">
          <div class="flex items-center space-x-3">
            <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" x="0px" y="0px" width="64" height="64" viewBox="0 0 64 64" stroke="currentColor" class="w-8 h-8 text-[#064161]">
              <path d="M 29 7 C 25.686 7 23 9.686 23 13 L 15 13 C 11.686 13 9 15.686 9 19 L 9 45 C 9 48.314 11.686 51 15 51 L 49 51 C 52.314 51 55 48.314 55 45 L 55 19 C 55 15.686 52.314 13 49 13 L 41 13 C 41 9.686 38.314 7 35 7 L 29 7 z M 29 11 L 35 11 C 36.104 11 37 11.895 37 13 L 27 13 C 27 11.895 27.896 11 29 11 z M 15 17 L 49 17 C 50.105 17 51 17.895 51 19 L 51 27.328125 C 47.860304 27.865386 40.276945 29 32 29 C 23.725715 29 16.142076 27.866066 13 27.328125 L 13 19 C 13 17.895 13.895 17 15 17 z M 13 31.384766 C 15.851521 31.855688 20.994182 32.574326 27 32.865234 L 27 33 C 27 34.105 27.895 35 29 35 L 34 35 C 35.105 35 36 34.105 36 33 L 36 32.917969 C 42.43805 32.665598 47.988855 31.881828 51 31.384766 L 51 45 C 51 46.105 50.105 47 49 47 L 15 47 C 13.895 47 13 46.105 13 45 L 13 31.384766 z"></path>
              </svg>
            <h4 class="text-xl text-[#064161]">The Political Weather</h4>
          </div>
          <svg class="accordion-icon w-5 h-5 text-[#064161] transform transition-transform" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
            <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path>
          </svg>
        </button>
        <div class="accordion-content hidden px-6 py-4">
          <div class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-[#064161] space-y-4">
            <p>
              The 1960s across South America was a pressure cooker of revolution, repression, and outside interference. Military coups toppled democracies in Brazil (’64), Argentina, and later Chile, while guerrilla movements gained ground in rural zones. Washington’s Cold War playbook was in full swing — the U.S. backed dictatorships to keep “red influence” at bay. Music inevitably became politicized: sometimes it was state-approved nationalism and “wholesome” folklore; other times it was underground protest, smuggled through metaphors and coded lyrics. For many artists, every chord carried a risk — of censorship, exile, or worse            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- What People Were Hearing -->
      <div class="accordion-item bg-white border border-[#FEE96A]/30 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
        <button class="accordion-trigger w-full px-6 py-4 text-left bg-[#FEE96A]/30 hover:bg-[#FEE96A]/20 transition-colors flex justify-between items-center">
          <div class="flex items-center space-x-3">
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-[#064161]" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M9 19V6l12-3v13M9 19c0 1.105-1.343 2-3 2s-3-.895-3-2 1.343-2 3-2 3 .895 3 2zm12-3c0 1.105-1.343 2-3 2s-3-.895-3-2 1.343-2 3-2 3 .895 3 2zM9 10l12-3"></path>
            </svg>
            <h4 class="text-xl text-[#064161]">What People Were Hearing</h4>
          </div>
          <svg class="accordion-icon w-5 h-5 text-[#064161] transform transition-transform" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
            <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path>
          </svg>
        </button>
        <div class="accordion-content hidden px-6 py-4">
          <div class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-[#064161] space-y-4">
            <p>
              Even before rock ’n’ roll’s arrival, the region already pulsed with sound. Indigenous Andean flutes, Afro-diasporic percussion, gaucho guitar ballads, coastal rhythms, and urban tango or samba created a rich base. In Colombia, cumbia — a hybrid of Indigenous, African, and Spanish traditions — was the sound of the people, already spreading far beyond its Caribbean coast birthplace. In Brazil, samba’s street energy softened into bossa nova: a smoky, café-ready form with jazz harmonies. Argentina held onto tango’s dramatic pull but was beginning to absorb modern jazz into its cafés. The whole continent was negotiating between folk roots and cosmopolitan modernity, between local identity and global pop.            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Scenes & Sounds That Emerged -->
      <div class="accordion-item bg-white border border-[#FEE96A]/30 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
        <button class="accordion-trigger w-full px-6 py-4 text-left bg-[#FEE96A]/30 hover:bg-[#FEE96A]/20 transition-colors flex justify-between items-center">
          <div class="flex items-center space-x-3">
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-[#064161]" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M13 10V3L4 14h7v7l9-11h-7z"></path>
            </svg>
            <h4 class="text-xl text-[#064161]">What you can find in this playlist</h4>
          </div>
          <svg class="accordion-icon w-5 h-5 text-[#064161] transform transition-transform" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
            <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path>
          </svg>
        </button>
        <div class="accordion-content hidden px-6 py-4">
          <div class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-[#064161] space-y-6">
            
            <!-- Brazil Subsection -->
            <div class="border-l-4 border-[#FEE96A] pl-4">
              <h5 class="text-lg font-bold text-[#064161] mb-2">Brazil</h5>
              <p class="mb-2">
                Bossa nova reshaped samba for living rooms and cafés: hushed vocals, nylon-string guitars, jazzy chords, and a sense of cool restraint. Later in the decade, Tropicália broke that cool wide open — taking fuzz guitars, tape experiments, samba rhythms, and psychedelic textures to challenge both tradition and dictatorship. Parallel to this, Música Popular Brasileira (MPB) became a catch-all for “serious” pop that mixed folk swing, jazz harmony, and poetic lyrics.
                </p>
            </div>

            <!-- Colombia Subsection -->
            <div class="border-l-4 border-[#C13870] pl-4">
              <h5 class="text-lg font-bold text-[#064161] mb-2">Colombia</h5>
              <p class="mb-2">
                Cumbia in the ’60s was brass-heavy, accordion-driven, and irresistible on dance floors. What had begun as a coastal folk style was becoming an urban craze, played in nightclubs, festivals, and radio. By this point, cumbia was already spreading across Latin America (notably Mexico, Peru, and Argentina), though its real explosion as a pan-Latin genre took off in the 70s.
</p>
            </div>

            <!-- Chile, Argentina, Uruguay Subsection -->
            <div class="border-l-4 border-[#FEE96A] pl-4">
              <h5 class="text-lg font-bold text-[#064161] mb-2">Chile, Argentina, Uruguay</h5>
              <p class="mb-2">
                The folk revival hardened into Nueva Canción. Traditional instruments like the charango, bombo, and quena were used not just to celebrate rural life but to tell stories of injustice, inequality, and resistance. The sound was stripped back, but the lyrics hit hard — turning village ballads into protest anthems.
</p>
            </div>

            <!-- Peru Subsection -->
            <div class="border-l-4 border-[#C13870] pl-4">
              <h5 class="text-lg font-bold text-[#064161] mb-2">Peru</h5>
              <p class="mb-2">
                Two wild currents emerged: garage rock and tropical fusion. Bands like Los Saicos cranked out distorted, chaotic proto-punk long before punk had a name. Meanwhile, “chicha” (Peruvian cumbia) blended Andean melodies with electric guitars and psychedelic reverb, creating a raw, hypnotic urban sound that was uniquely Peruvian.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

<!-- Technological changes -->
      <BeachvilleAccordionItem title="Technological changes">
        <div slot="icon">
          <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-[#064161]" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
            <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M9.75 17L9 20l-1 1h8l-1-1-.75-3M3 13h18M5 17h14a2 2 0 002-2V5a2 2 0 00-2-2H5a2 2 0 00-2 2v10a2 2 0 002 2z"></path>
          </svg>
        </div>
        <div slot="content">
          <div class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-[#064161] space-y-4">
            The 1960s were when technology reshaped South American soundscapes:<br/>
            <BeachvilleListItem title="Electric guitars" borderColor="border-[#FEE96A]">
              <div slot="content">
                Electric guitars were everywhere — cheap imports meant teenagers in Bogotá, São Paulo, and Lima were starting bands overnight.
              </div>
            </BeachvilleListItem>
            <BeachvilleListItem title="Transistor radios" borderColor="border-[#C13870]">
              <div slot="content">
            Electric guitars were everywhere — cheap imports meant teenagers in Bogotá, São Paulo, and Lima were starting bands overnight.
              </div>
            </BeachvilleListItem>
            <BeachvilleListItem title="Vinyl and local pressing plants" borderColor="border-[#FEE96A]">
              <div slot="content">
                Vinyl and local pressing plants meant regional hits could circulate nationally and, in some cases, across borders.
              </div>
            </BeachvilleListItem>
            <BeachvilleListItem title="Televised song festivals" borderColor="border-[#C13870]">
              <div slot="content">
                Televised song festivals in Brazil (e.g. Popular network -  TV Record’s Festival de Música Popular Brasileira) became the platform for new music. These weren’t just competitions — they were national broadcasts where new movements (bossa nova, MPB, Tropicália) reached living rooms instantly.
              </div>
            </BeachvilleListItem>
          </div>
        </div>
      </BeachvilleAccordionItem>
     

      <!-- Notable Artists -->
      <div class="accordion-item bg-white border border-[#FEE96A]/30 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
        <button class="accordion-trigger w-full px-6 py-4 text-left bg-[#FEE96A]/30 hover:bg-[#FEE96A]/20 transition-colors flex justify-between items-center">
          <div class="flex items-center space-x-3">
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-[#064161]" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M16 7a4 4 0 11-8 0 4 4 0 018 0zM12 14a7 7 0 00-7 7h14a7 7 0 00-7-7z"></path>
            </svg>
              <h4 class="text-xl text-[#064161]">Notable Artists</h4>
          </div>
          <svg class="accordion-icon w-5 h-5 text-[#064161] transform transition-transform" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
            <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path>
          </svg>
        </button>
        <div class="accordion-content hidden px-6 py-4">
          <div class="space-y-6">
            <BeachvilleArtistSection data={data} />
            </div>

          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<script>
  // Accordion functionality
  document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
    const accordionTriggers = document.querySelectorAll('.accordion-trigger');
    
    accordionTriggers.forEach(trigger => {
      trigger.addEventListener('click', () => {
        const accordionItem = trigger.closest('.accordion-item');
        const content = accordionItem?.querySelector('.accordion-content');
        const icon = trigger.querySelector('.accordion-icon');
        
        if (content && icon) {
          const isOpen = !content.classList.contains('hidden');
          

          
          // Toggle current accordion
          if (isOpen) {
            content.classList.add('hidden');
            icon.classList.remove('rotate-180');
          } else {
            content.classList.remove('hidden');
            icon.classList.add('rotate-180');
          }
        }
      });
    });
  });
</script>


